57th Mage Innoruuk <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uchardandhispet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chard and his pet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#333333>(8/23/02 8:11:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=250.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How do you chaincast? </span><hr size=1> I spent a lot of time in my low 50s chaincasting the Seafuries, it's great cos a single pet with a DS is all that's needed.  Very mana efficient and the xp and loot are reliable.<br>
<br>
I also got some more advanced training when I soloed Slixin Klex with chaincasting.  It was just about doable at level 52 with my 200int at that time.  It took 6 or 7 pets, each pet lasting about one minute, Klex has a low range so you can med close by, but watch out: he can quad for 137!  Couple of times I ran out of mana and had to run for zone, heartbreaking when your target is nearly dead after a 10 minute fight.  Now with all pets at max strength, Klex should be ideal training material.<br>
<br>
I tried the same technique on Tarbul Earthstrider, but his reach is much greater and he runs faster.  I didn't try him too many times... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uithryn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ithryn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#333333>(8/23/02 12:37:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=250.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How do you chaincast? </span><hr size=1> The reach of the mob should no longer make any difference.  You can issue the /pet get lost command from all the way across the zone if you need to. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uyarril.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yarril</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#333333>(9/6/02 4:35:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=250.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How do you chaincast? </span><hr size=1> You should be able to hotkey/macro it fairly reliably using something like the following (again, assuming 8 is your pet gem)<br>
<br>
/cast 8<br>
/cast 8<br>
/cast 8<br>
/pause 90, /cast 8<br>
/pet get lost<br>
<br>
Where the 90 pause (9.0 seconds) assumes say a 10 second casting time, and kills the existing pet about 1 second before the spell completes.  Adjust to suit your setup.  The 4 /cast 8s this gives you pretty much ensures you will never fizzle it (unless you think there is a chance you might fizzle 4 times in a row).<br>
<br>
Note that if you have packet-loss or long lag times on your connection, this sort of macro is a bad idea, since it won't protect you properly from fizzles.  It also may lead to your existing pet not being killed before the new pet is summoned, or the old pet being killed too early.  Use with care!<br>
